# CLAUDE.md — context: [APP-NAME]

This file is dropped into the working directory of `[APP-NAME]` by `setup-server.sh`. It defines the scoped rules for any LLM session started from `[APP-NAME]`'s production path. The global rules in `<vault>/CLAUDE.md` always apply too — this file *adds* per-app constraints.

## Who you are

- Application: **[APP-NAME]**
- Framework: [framework + version]
- Server: [N]
- Vault path: `[/home/USER/vault]`

## Allowed writes in the vault

- `wiki/apps/[APP-NAME]/**` — full write
- `wiki/integrations/NN-*` — you are the **producer**, full write (list each contract)
- `wiki/integrations/NN-*` — Consumer notes section ONLY (list each contract you consume)
- `wiki/flows/[flow-where-this-app-initiates].md` — you are the main participant
- `wiki/log.md` — append-only

## FORBIDDEN writes

- `wiki/apps/{any-other-app}/**`
- `wiki/decisions/**` — proposals go in `wiki/apps/[APP-NAME]/proposed-adr/`
- `wiki/integrations/` outside the contracts listed above
- `wiki/index.md` (regenerated by lint)
- Files under `raw/` (immutable)

## Integrations involving this app

| ID | Page | Role | Subject |
|---|---|---|---|
| NN | `NN-...md` | **producer** / consumer | [what flows through it] |
| NN | `NN-...md` | producer / **consumer** | [what flows through it] |

## Local quirks

[Anything specific to this app that future sessions should know:
- Critical code paths
- Recurring failure modes
- Constraints that aren't obvious from the code
- Stakeholders who care about specific modules]

## Writing conventions

- Bugs that took > 30 min → page in `wiki/apps/[APP-NAME]/debugging/YYYY-MM-slug.md`
- Major modules → `wiki/apps/[APP-NAME]/modules/`
- Critical-situation runbooks → `wiki/apps/[APP-NAME]/runbooks/`
- Proposed ADRs → `wiki/apps/[APP-NAME]/proposed-adr/`
- Contract changes → "Breaking changes log" entry on the relevant integration page (producer only)
- Session log entry → `wiki/log.md`

## Never touch

- `.env`, config files, credentials of any kind
- Real customer data, PII, anything regulated under privacy law
